results.notes:
On HCL- shale cobbles. Thallus of brown dispersed areoles, some becoming slightly subsquamulose. Dark brown in full sun, greenish in shade side. Cortex and medulla C-, cortex paraplectenchymatous. Algal layer continuous. Apothecia 1(2) per areole, deeply immersed, without a parathecial ring but having a thalline collar somewhat raised, disk concave, epruinose, dark reddish brown to nearly black. Epihymenium reddish in thick sections, light orange in thin ones. Hymenium hyaline, ~150µm tall including epihymenium. Paraphyses long and thin, scarcely widened at tip, not branched.

Spores large, simple, hyaline, ellipsoid (egg shaped), estimated 30-40 per ascus. Average size: 12.7×6.5 (n=6).

results.notes:
Macro: thallus an olive green under thick white coating (epinecral layer?). White coating intermittent, giving thallus a mottled look. Lower parts of thallus often superficially orangeish, appears to be discolored part of the white stuff on top of the thallus. Underlying thallus an olive green color. Apothecia black, concave, ranging from completely white-pruinose to epruinose. Larger aps ~0.5 mm diam. I think the white areas of the thallus are largely obscuring what would be white rims around the apothecia (visible in some tiny, developing aps).

Micro: Cortex hyaline, cellular, with dark brown upper layer and topped with epinecral layer (?), 30-50 µm not including epinecral layer. Conidia short, <10µm (6, 7, 5, 6, 8 µm long; 3/16/21: measured a bunch of conidia, measurement all falling basically between 6-8 um long), ~1-2 um wide. Hymenium incl. epihym: ~155 µm. Epihymenium: olive green.

4 Spores measured: 24.3 × 18.6; 22.1 × 18.1; 23.9 × 18.4; 22.0×16.7 µm

results.notes:
The small, young Eastern Red Cedar & Virginia Pine forest where I found this specimen (and several others like it) is extremely perplexing to me. It appears to be less than 20 years old, and it’s a relatively narrow strip well under an acre. I discovered it in August of 2020, and from August through October it had a shocking diversity and quantity of fungi. An incomplete list of the species I found there (excluding the many lichens): Clitocybe nuda*, Amanita muscaria var guessowi, Lactarius indigo*, Lactarius chelidonium*, Lactarius deliciosus var deterrimus*, Lactarius paradoxus, Lactarius subpurpureus, Tricholoma equestre* Amanita rubescens, Hypomyces hyalinus, Glutinoglossum glutinosum*, Calvatia spp, Lycoperdon perlatum*, Laccaria laccata*, and probably several more that I’m forgetting. *=over 100 specimens at once. Many of these were fruiting simultaneously and densely packed!
If anyone has theories as to why a young cedar-dominant strip of forest containted the greatest fungal biodiversity of anywhere I experienced in 2020, I’d love to hear them.

results.notes:
We collected the same species, exactly one year after, as observation MO404039.
Growing on the foothills with grass under sagebrush, with no other close trees. No signs of growing on wood, but there were signs of a burn from a few years back.
The pictures look about the same, but showing more of the scales and veil on the stipe.
Cap up to 5 cms, viscid, orange first later more yellow-brown, glabrous. The stipe 1.3 cms. × 5 cms., white, with some fibrils and more scaly and darker below.
Microscopically, I believe the pileipellis is a mixed Ixocutis, narrowly cylindrical, has abundant pleurocystidia fusioform-ventricose 46×16×7, and the spores are smooth, elliptical without a obvious germ pore, (6.5-7.2) x (4.1-4.5); Q=1.64.
This observations point in my opinion to Pholiota subg. Flammuloides, probably sect. Carbonicola; as Pholiota cf. molesta.
These samples are a little bigger that my references, but I see a few inconsistences on the cap diameter between molesta (2cm)- highlandensis (5cm), after endorsing P. molesta as common in the west USA. The stem is tapered down, and is also a little over the ref. on the thickest part.
MATHENY ET AL.: POST-FIRE PHOLIOTA IN NORTH AMERICA on page 16 run some hypothesis about how the burn areas get colonized; the question I ask myself is, for how many years after a fire can we made aware of their existence?
